        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":16,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":10,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":14,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy (walk/run as needed)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"James, this is your re-entry phase. Every run stays at your easy pace ceiling of 5:58/km — no exceptions. Sessions cap at 20 minutes per your physio clearance. Three days per week (e.g., Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday long run). If foot pain appears mid-run, shift immediately to a walk-run pattern: 3 minutes easy running, 2 minutes walking, repeat. Weekly distance builds by no more than 10% week-over-week. A deload week occurs in week 4, dropping back to week 2 volume. Cross-training (swimming, cycling) is encouraged on off days to maintain aerobic fitness without foot loading. The goal here is not fitness — it is tissue tolerance and confidence. Every pain-free minute is a win.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":14,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":20,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90% easy / 10% cross-train\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":342,\"notes\":\"If you have received clearance from your physiotherapist to extend beyond 20 minutes, this phase begins cautiously stretching run duration — first to 25 minutes, then 30 minutes by week 8. If you are still capped at 20 minutes, volume growth comes from adding a fourth short run day rather than extending individual sessions. Pace remains in the easy band (5:24–5:58/km). No speed work yet. A deload week occurs in week 8. The focus is building consistent weekly mileage and letting the plantar fascia adapt progressively. Listen carefully to morning foot stiffness — it is one of the best early signals of tissue overload.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":20,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":28,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% moderate (tempo only if cleared for speed work)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":324,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"This phase only introduces tempo work if your physiotherapist has explicitly cleared you for speed work by this point. If not, all runs remain easy and volume continues to build. Assuming clearance: one tempo session per week, capped at 10–15 minutes of tempo effort within a longer easy run — never a standalone hard session. Tempo pace is 4:29/km per your VDOT. Long run on Saturday extends to 45–50 minutes. A deload week occurs in week 12. Your VDOT of 46.5 reflects your pre-injury fitness; current fitness is likely meaningfully lower, so these paces are targets to grow into, not benchmarks to hit on day one. Process over pace.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":28,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":32,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85% easy / 15% moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":324,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":284,\"notes\":\"This final phase consolidates your rebuilt base and establishes a sustainable training rhythm you can carry forward into a future race-specific plan. Volume stabilizes rather than continuing to climb — the goal is consistency and confidence, not peak fitness. Long runs reach 60 minutes. One optional moderate effort per week if feeling strong and pain-free. A deload week in week 16 brings the plan to a close on a recovery note, leaving you fresh and ready to set your next goal. By the end of this phase, you should have a clear conversation with your physio about what racing goals are realistic for the next 3–6 months.\",\"includes_deload\":true}],\"rationale\":\"James, here is the thinking behind this plan. You have a strong foundation — five years of experience and a 44:00 10K tells me you know how to train. But plantar fasciitis is one of those injuries that genuinely rewards patience and punishes impatience, so this plan is built around a single principle: earn the right to do more. Your physio has cleared you for 20-minute easy runs only, with no speed work. That clearance is the ceiling for Phase 1, full stop. The 10% weekly volume rule is not just a guideline here — it is a hard guardrail, because plantar fascia tissue adapts more slowly than your cardiovascular system. You will feel ready to do more before your foot is ready to handle more. That gap is where re-injury lives. All paces are derived from your pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 using Daniels' Running Formula, but your current fitness is almost certainly lower after the layoff. Use the easy pace range (5:24–5:58/km) as a ceiling, not a target — starting at 5:58/km is completely appropriate and smart. The three-days-per-week structure respects both your preference and your injury, giving the plantar fascia genuine recovery time between sessions. Cross-training on off days is strongly encouraged to maintain aerobic base without adding foot stress. Speed work does not appear until Phase 3, and only conditionally — your physio's clearance gates that decision, not the calendar.\",\"warnings\":\"IMPORTANT: This plan is built around your current physiotherapist clearance for 20-minute easy runs with no speed work. Do not progress to Phase 3 tempo work without explicit physio clearance for speed work, regardless of how good your foot feels. Morning heel pain or stiffness that lasts more than 10 minutes after getting out of bed is a key warning sign of plantar fasciitis flare — if this occurs, drop back to walk-run intervals and contact your physiotherapist before your next run. Do not redistribute missed mileage to other days. If you miss a session, simply continue from where you are. This plan does not replace medical advice. Any increase in foot pain should be assessed by your physiotherapist before continuing. Your pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 is used for pace calculations, but current fitness is likely lower — treat all paces as upper limits, not minimums.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
